# One of the performance patterns to analyze is the customers who bought a product. This can be found in the Revenue column. 
# This shows how many customers made a purchase while visiting the website. Hence, to plot the number of customers who have 
# brought revenue to the organization that is those with the value 'true' and those who visited the page but did not make a 
# purchase with the value 'false' 

import seaborn as sns
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
total=float(len(df2))
ax = sns.countplot(x="Revenue", data=df2)
for p in ax.patches:
    percentage ='{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
    x = p.get_x() + p.get_width()
    y = p.get_height()
    ax.annotate (percentage, (x,y), ha='center')
    plt.show()

# Another pattern that can be useful is an assessment of the visitor type during weekend. By understanding if the people visiting 
# the website during the weekend are returning visitors or new visitors, it is possible to know how better to allocate advertisment
# resources during the weekend or towards the weekend.

x,y = 'VisitorType', 'Weekend'
df1 = df2.groupby(x)[y].value_counts(normalize=True)
df1 = df1.mul(100)
df1 = df1.rename('percent').reset_index()
g = sns.catplot(x=x, y='percent', hue=y, kind='bar', data=df1)
g.ax.set_ylim(0,100)
for p in g.ax.patches:
    txt = str(p.get_height().round(2)) + '%'
    txt_x = p.get_x()
    txt_y = p.get_height()
    g.ax.text(txt_x, txt_y, txt)

# Clustering the data makes it easier to analyse the data. This makes it possible to segment the data into efficient groups that 
# ensure accurate results are attained. The clustering will be done using the K-means cluster analysis. This code prepares the 
# data, and checks for the shape of the dataset before clustering it. By creating a plot using the elbow method, it is possible 
# to determine the number of clusters that can be derived from the dataset

x = df2.iloc[:, [1, 6]].values
x.shape
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
wcss = []
for i in range (1,11):
    km= KMeans(n_clusters = i,
              init = 'k-means++',
              max_iter = 300,
              n_init = 10,
              random_state = 0,
              algorithm = 'elkan',
              tol = 0.001)
    km.fit(x)
    labels = km.labels_
    wcss.append(km.inertia_)
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (15,7)
plt.plot(range (1, 11), wcss)
plt.grid()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.title('The Elbow Method', fontsize = 20)
plt.xlabel('No. of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('wcss')
plt.show()

  warnings.warn(
In [33]:
# Given the results from the elbow method above, the maximum bend is at the third index. Thus the number of optimal number of 
# clusters for administrative duration and revenue is three. Hence to plot the clusters the code below can be used:

km = KMeans(n_clusters = 3, init = 'k-means++', max_iter = 300, n_init = 10, random_state = 0)
y_means = km.fit_predict(x)
plt.scatter(x[y_means ==0, 0], x[y_means == 0, 1], s = 100, c = 'red', label = 'Un-interested Customers')
plt.scatter(x[y_means == 1,0], x[y_means == 1, 1], s = 100, c = 'yellow', label = 'General Customers')
plt.scatter(x[y_means == 2,0], x[y_means == 2, 1], s = 100, c = 'green', label = 'Target Customers')
plt.scatter(km.cluster_centers_[:,0], km.cluster_centers_[:,1], s = 50, c = 'blue', label = 'centeroid')
plt.title('Administrative Duration vs Duration', fontsize = 20)
plt.grid()
plt.xlabel('Administrative Duration')
plt.ylabel('Bounce Rates')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
